    differentiationNotes: `Struggling learners benefit from identifying three common prefixes and suffixes and explaining how they change a word\u2019s meaning, such as how \u2018un-\u2019 means not so \u2018unhappy\u2019 means not happy and \u2018-ful\u2019 means full of so \u2018helpful\u2019 means full of help, and using a dictionary to find definitions and word origins for familiar words. Advanced learners benefit from analyzing how Latin and Greek roots appear across word families, such as tracing how the root \u2018struct\u2019 meaning to build connects construct, structure, instruct, destruct, and infrastructure, and researching and comparing three different writing systems in a multi-paragraph report analyzing the advantages and limitations of alphabets, syllabaries, and logographic systems.`,
    parentTakeaway: `Alphabet as language science \u2014 explore word origins together using a dictionary\u2019s etymology entries to discover where familiar words come from and how their original meanings connect to current usage; play word-building games with prefixes and suffixes where you take a root word and see how many new words you can create by adding different affixes; compare how different languages write the same sounds by looking at words borrowed between languages or examining different writing systems in books or online; use reading for vocabulary-building discussions by pausing when encountering unfamiliar words and modeling how to break them into roots and affixes to predict meaning before checking the dictionary.`,
    classroomIntegration: `Etymology investigation station with root word detective activities where students trace word families from Latin and Greek roots, building vocabulary webs connecting related words through shared morphemes, writing systems comparison research project where students investigate and present findings on how alphabets, syllabaries, and logographic systems each approach the challenge of representing language in written form, dictionary skills practice center where students use guide words for rapid searching, interpret pronunciation keys and etymology entries, and determine the correct definition for words with multiple meanings in specific contexts, spelling pattern analysis with word sorting activities where students categorize words by their origin language based on spelling patterns such as Greek-origin words with \u2018ph\u2019 and Latin-origin words with \u2018-tion\u2019, and expository writing workshop on language topics where students compose multi-paragraph texts integrating mathematical data from letter frequency analysis and language comparison calculations.`,
